[1]
Date: Sun 14 Dec 2008
Source: The Irish Times, Press Association (PA) report [edited]
<http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2008/1214/breaking7.htm>


Northern Ireland authorities investigate suspected rabies case
--------------------------------------------------------------
A suspected case of rabies is being investigated in Northern Ireland. The
patient was taken ill after returning from overseas in an area associated
with the infection and may have been bitten there. Initial tests on the
patient proved positive and further tests are being carried out to confirm
the diagnosis. There is no treatment for the infection, which is always
fatal, according to the medical authorities.

The Eastern Health and Social Services Board in Belfast is leading a
multi-agency investigation into what it said was "a highly likely case of
human rabies." The patient was initially treated in the Ulster Hospital at
Dundonald on the outskirts of Belfast and is now in the Royal Victoria
Hospital in the city. The board insisted the risk to the wider community
was negligible -- there [has been] no documented case of human to human
transmission of rabies anywhere in the world. It added that the person
poses no risk to other patients or to visitors. Both hospitals are
functioning normally and there is no risk to the provision of their
services. "All necessary steps on infection control are in place for the
protection of staff."

Rabies is a notifiable disease in Northern Ireland and there have been no
notifications of rabies in humans there since 1938. The board and its
partner agencies are taking national expert advice from the Health
Protection Agency and the Veterinary Laboratories Agency. It added: "The
board and its partner agencies are satisfied that all necessary steps to
protect public health are in place and again stress that any risk to the
community is negligible."

