******
[2]
Date: Sun 14 Dec 2008
Source: BBC News, Northern Ireland [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/7782229.stm>


Patient awaits tests for rabies
-------------------------------
Further tests are being carried out to confirm whether a patient at a
hospital in Belfast has rabies. Initial tests were positive. The patient
had been abroad but began to feel unwell after they [the patient] had been
home for several months.

The Eastern Health Board said it was leading a multi-agency investigation
but stressed the risk to the wider community was "negligible".

The patient is being treated at the Royal Victoria Hospital in Belfast. The
board and its partner agencies are taking advice from the Health Protection
Agency and the Veterinary Laboratories Agency. Rabies is extremely rare in
the United Kingdom and there have only been 23 known cases since 1946. The
last known case of rabies in Northern Ireland was in 1938.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[These reports do not reveal the nature of the test employed to confirm the
preliminary diagnosis of rabies virus infection. Strangely the country (or
countries) of potential exposure of the patient to rabies virus infection
is/are not stated, nor is it certain that the patient had been bitten by a
potentially rabid animal.

According to the CDC (US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention)
website <http://www.cdc.gov/healthypets/diseases/rabies.htm> it may take
several weeks or even a few years for people to show symptoms after getting
infected with rabies, but usually people start to show signs of the disease
one to 3 months after the virus infects them. The early signs of rabies can
be fever or headache, but this changes quickly to nervous system signs,
such as confusion, sleepiness, or agitation. Once someone with rabies
infection starts having these symptoms, that person usually does not survive.

Further information is awaited.

The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of the United Kingdom at
<http://healthmap.org/promed/en?g=2641364&v=54.5,-6.5,5> can be used to
located Northern Ireland and the city of Belfast. - Mod.CP]
